<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900410-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>900410-0030.</DOCID><HL>   Thyssen's Budd Co. Unit   Agrees to Pay $1.5 Million</HL><DATE>04/10/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13</SO><CO>   G.THY LABOR</CO><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Budd Co. agreed to pay $1.5 million tosettle Labor Department charges of workplace noise and othersafety and health violations at the company's Philadelphiaautomotive-panel plant.   Budd also agreed to set up corporatewide worker-hearingconservation and record-keeping programs, the department'sOccupational Safety and Health Administration said. Budd,based in Troy, Mich., and a unit of Thyssen AG in WestGermany, agreed to the settlement without admitting thealleged violations.</LP><TEXT>   OSHA last December proposed penalties totaling $3.3million against Budd for the alleged Philadelphia violations.But as with many accords, the regulatory agency agreed to thesmaller fine in return for a commitment for corporatewideabatement of the alleged unsafe practices.   At the time, the $3.3 million was the fourth-largestproposed penalty for a company in OSHA history. The agencyhad charged Budd with noise-rule violations, includingfailure to tell workers they had suffered hearing loss and tohave doctors review problem cases; with violations ofengineering-control regulations; and with willful violationsof record-keeping rules, such as the required notation ofmedical treatment for injuries.   The agreement calls for Budd to reduce excessive noise atthe Philadelphia plant by April 30, 1991, and to begin ahearing-conservation program at all its facilities by Sept.1, 1990.   Budd also will audit injury and illness record-keepingsince Jan. 1, 1987, to see that the records comply withfederal requirements, and to keep future records incompliance, OSHA said.</TEXT></DOC>